[src:dinic-algorithm/dinic-s-algorithm] Dinitz invented the algorithm in January 1969, as a master's student in Georgy Adelson-Velsky's group.
[src:dinic-algorithm/dinic-s-algorithm] In 1970, Dinitz published a description of the algorithm in *Doklady Akademii Nauk SSSR*.
[src:dinic-algorithm/dinic-s-algorithm] In 1974, Shimon Even and (his then Ph.D. student) Alon Itai at the Technion in Haifa were very curious and intrigued by Dinitz's algorithm as well as Alexander V.
[src:dinic-algorithm/dinic-s-algorithm] Karzanov's related idea of blocking flow.
[src:dinic-algorithm/dinic-s-algorithm] However it was hard for them to decipher these two papers, each being limited to four pages to meet the restrictions of journal *Doklady Akademii Nauk SSSR*.
[src:dinic-algorithm/dinic-s-algorithm] Even did not give up, and after three days of effort managed to understand both papers except for the layered network maintenance issue.
[src:dinic-algorithm/dinic-s-algorithm] Over the next couple of years, Even gave lectures on "Dinic's algorithm", mispronouncing the name of the author while popularizing it.
[src:dinic-algorithm/dinic-s-algorithm] Even and Itai also contributed to this algorithm by combining BFS and DFS, which is how the algorithm is now commonly presented.
[src:dinic-algorithm/dinic-s-algorithm] For about 10 years of time after the Ford–Fulkerson algorithm was invented, it was unknown if it could be made to terminate in polynomial time in the general case of irrational edge capacities.
[src:dinic-algorithm/dinic-s-algorithm] This caused a lack of any known polynomial-time algorithm to solve the max flow problem in generic cases.
[src:dinic-algorithm/dinic-s-algorithm] Dinitz's algorithm and the Edmonds–Karp algorithm (published in 1972) both independently showed that in the Ford–Fulkerson algorithm, if each augmenting path is the shortest one, then the length of the augmenting paths is non-decreasing and the algorithm always terminates.
[src:dinic-algorithm/dinic-s-algorithm] Let $G=((V,E),c,f,s,t)$ be a network with $c(u,v)$ and $f(u,v)$ the capacity and the flow of the edge $(u,v)$ , respectively.
[src:dinic-algorithm/dinic-s-algorithm] If $\operatorname {dist} (t)=\infty$ , stop and output f .
[src:dinic-algorithm/dinic-s-algorithm] Augment flow f by $f'$ and go back to step 2.
[src:dinic-algorithm/dinic-s-algorithm] It can be shown that the number of layers in each blocking flow increases by at least 1 each time and thus there are at most $|V|-1$ blocking flows in the algorithm.
[src:dinic-algorithm/dinic-s-algorithm] with total running time $O(E+VE)=O(VE)$ for each layer.
[src:dinic-algorithm/dinic-s-algorithm] As a consequence, the running time of Dinic's algorithm is $O(V^{2}E)$ .
[src:dinic-algorithm/dinic-s-algorithm] Using a data structure called dynamic trees, the running time of finding a blocking flow in each phase can be reduced to $O(E\log V)$ and therefore the running time of Dinic's algorithm can be improved to $O(VE\log V)$ .
[src:dinic-algorithm/dinic-s-algorithm] In networks with unit capacities, a much stronger time bound holds.
[src:dinic-algorithm/dinic-s-algorithm] Each blocking flow can be found in $O(E)$ time, and it can be shown that the number of phases does not exceed $O({\sqrt {E}})$ and $O(V^{2/3})$ .
[src:dinic-algorithm/dinic-s-algorithm] In networks that arise from the bipartite matching problem, the number of phases is bounded by $O({\sqrt {V}})$ , therefore leading to the $O({\sqrt {V}}E)$ time bound.
[src:dinic-algorithm/dinic-s-algorithm] The resulting algorithm is also known as Hopcroft–Karp algorithm.
[src:dinic-algorithm/dinic-s-algorithm] More generally, this bound holds for any *unit network* — a network in which each vertex, except for source and sink, either has a single entering edge of capacity one, or a single outgoing edge of capacity one, and all other capacities are arbitrary integers.
[src:dinic-algorithm/dinic-s-algorithm] The following is a simulation of Dinic's algorithm.
[src:dinic-algorithm/dinic-s-algorithm] In the level graph $G_{L}$ , the vertices with labels in red are the values $\operatorname {dist} (v)$ .
[src:dinic-algorithm/flow-network] In graph theory, a **flow network** (also known as a **transportation network**) is a directed graph where each edge has a **capacity** and each edge receives a flow.
[src:dinic-algorithm/flow-network] The amount of flow on an edge cannot exceed the capacity of the edge.
[src:dinic-algorithm/flow-network] Often in operations research, a directed graph is called a **network**, the vertices are called **nodes** and the edges are called **arcs**.
[src:dinic-algorithm/flow-network] A flow must satisfy the restriction that the amount of flow into a node equals the amount of flow out of it, unless it is a **source**, which has only outgoing flow, or **sink**, which has only incoming flow.
[src:dinic-algorithm/flow-network] A flow network can be used to model traffic in a computer network, circulation with demands, fluids in pipes, currents in an electrical circuit, or anything similar in which something travels through a network of nodes.
[src:dinic-algorithm/flow-network] As such, efficient algorithms for solving network flows can also be applied to solve problems that can be reduced to a flow network, including survey design, airline scheduling, image segmentation, and the matching problem.
[src:dinic-algorithm/flow-network] A **network** is a directed graph *G* = (*V*, *E*) with a non-negative **capacity** function *c* for each edge, and without multiple arcs (i.e. edges with the same source and target nodes).
[src:dinic-algorithm/flow-network] Without loss of generality, we may assume that if (*u*, *v*) ∈ *E*, then (*v*, *u*) is also a member of E.
[src:dinic-algorithm/flow-network] If two nodes in G are distinguished – one as the source s and the other as the sink t – then (*G*, *c*, *s*, *t*) is called a **flow network**.
[src:dinic-algorithm/flow-network] In flow networks, the source s is deficient, and the sink t is active.
[src:dinic-algorithm/flow-network] Pseudo-flows, feasible flows, and pre-flows are all examples of flow functions.
[src:dinic-algorithm/flow-network] The **value** |*f*| of a feasible flow f for a network, is the net flow into the sink t of the flow network, that is: |*f*| = *x**f* (*t*).
[src:dinic-algorithm/flow-network] Note, the flow value in a network is also equal to the total outgoing flow of source s, that is: |*f*| = −*x**f* (*s*).
[src:dinic-algorithm/flow-network] Also, if we define *A* as a set of nodes in *G* such that *s* ∈ *A* and *t* ∉ *A*, the flow value is equal to the total net flow going out of A (i.e. |*f*| = *f* out(*A*) − *f* in(*A*)).
[src:dinic-algorithm/flow-network] The flow value in a network is the total amount of flow from s to t.
[src:dinic-algorithm/flow-network] Flow decomposition is a process of breaking down a given flow into a collection of path flows and cycle flows.
[src:dinic-algorithm/flow-network] Every flow through a network can be decomposed into one or more paths and corresponding quantities, such that each edge in the flow equals the sum of all quantities of paths that pass through it.
[src:dinic-algorithm/flow-network] Flow decomposition is a powerful tool in optimization problems to maximize or minimize specific flow parameters.
[src:dinic-algorithm/flow-network] We do not use multiple arcs within a network because we can combine those arcs into a single arc.
[src:dinic-algorithm/flow-network] Along with the other constraints, the skew symmetry constraint must be remembered during this step to maintain the direction of the original pseudo-flow arc.
[src:dinic-algorithm/flow-network] Adding flow to an arc is the same as adding an arc with the capacity of zero.
[src:dinic-algorithm/flow-network] The **residual capacity** of an arc e with respect to a pseudo-flow f is denoted *c**f*, and it is the difference between the arc's capacity and its flow.
[src:dinic-algorithm/flow-network] From this we can construct a **residual network**, denoted *G**f* (*V*, *E**f*), with a capacity function *c**f* which models the amount of *available* capacity on the set of arcs in *G* = (*V*, *E*).
[src:dinic-algorithm/flow-network] More specifically, capacity function *c**f* of each arc (*u*, *v*) in the residual network represents the amount of flow which can be transferred from u to v given the current state of the flow within the network.
[src:dinic-algorithm/flow-network] This concept is used in Ford–Fulkerson algorithm which computes the maximum flow in a flow network.
[src:dinic-algorithm/flow-network] Note that there can be an unsaturated path (a path with available capacity) from u to v in the residual network, even though there is no such path from u to v in the original network.
[src:dinic-algorithm/flow-network] Since flows in opposite directions cancel out, *decreasing* the flow from v to u is the same as *increasing* the flow from u to v.
[src:dinic-algorithm/flow-network] More simply, an augmenting path is an available flow path from the source to the sink.
[src:dinic-algorithm/flow-network] A network is at maximum flow if and only if there is no augmenting path in the residual network *G**f*.
[src:dinic-algorithm/flow-network] The **bottleneck** is the minimum residual capacity of all the edges in a given augmenting path.
[src:dinic-algorithm/flow-network] See example explained in the "Example" section of this article.
[src:dinic-algorithm/flow-network] The flow network is at maximum flow if and only if it has a bottleneck with a value equal to zero.
[src:dinic-algorithm/flow-network] If any augmenting path exists, its bottleneck weight will be greater than 0.
[src:dinic-algorithm/flow-network] In other words, if there is a bottleneck value greater than 0, then there is an augmenting path from the source to the sink.
[src:dinic-algorithm/flow-network] However, we know that if there is any augmenting path, then the network is not at maximum flow, which in turn means that, if there is a bottleneck value greater than 0, then the network is not at maximum flow.
[src:dinic-algorithm/flow-network] The term "augmenting the flow" for an augmenting path means updating the flow f of each arc in this augmenting path to equal the capacity *c* of the bottleneck.
[src:dinic-algorithm/flow-network] Augmenting the flow corresponds to pushing additional flow along the augmenting path until there is no remaining available residual capacity in the bottleneck.
[src:dinic-algorithm/flow-network] Sometimes, when modeling a network with more than one source, a **supersource** is introduced to the graph.
[src:dinic-algorithm/flow-network] This consists of a vertex connected to each of the sources with edges of infinite capacity, so as to act as a global source.
[src:dinic-algorithm/flow-network] A similar construct for sinks is called a **supersink**.
[src:dinic-algorithm/flow-network] In Figure 1 you see a flow network with source labeled s, sink t, and four additional nodes.
[src:dinic-algorithm/flow-network] The flow and capacity is denoted $f/c$ .
[src:dinic-algorithm/flow-network] Notice how the network upholds the capacity constraint and flow conservation constraint.
[src:dinic-algorithm/flow-network] The total amount of flow from s to t is 5, which can be easily seen from the fact that the total outgoing flow from s is 5, which is also the incoming flow to t.
[src:dinic-algorithm/flow-network] By the skew symmetry constraint, from c to a is -2 because the flow from a to c is 2.
[src:dinic-algorithm/flow-network] In Figure 2 you see the residual network for the same given flow.
[src:dinic-algorithm/flow-network] Notice how there is positive residual capacity on some edges where the original capacity is zero in Figure 1, for example for the edge $(d,c)$ .
[src:dinic-algorithm/flow-network] There is available capacity along the paths $(s,a,c,t)$ , $(s,a,b,d,t)$ and $(s,a,b,d,c,t)$ , which are then the augmenting paths.
[src:dinic-algorithm/flow-network] Picture a series of water pipes, fitting into a network.
[src:dinic-algorithm/flow-network] Each pipe is of a certain diameter, so it can only maintain a flow of a certain amount of water.
[src:dinic-algorithm/flow-network] Anywhere that pipes meet, the total amount of water coming into that junction must be equal to the amount going out, otherwise we would quickly run out of water, or we would have a buildup of water.
[src:dinic-algorithm/flow-network] We have a water inlet, which is the source, and an outlet, the sink.
[src:dinic-algorithm/flow-network] A flow would then be one possible way for water to get from source to sink so that the total amount of water coming out of the outlet is consistent.
[src:dinic-algorithm/flow-network] Intuitively, the total flow of a network is the rate at which water comes out of the outlet.
[src:dinic-algorithm/flow-network] Flows can pertain to people or material over transportation networks, or to electricity over electrical distribution systems.
[src:dinic-algorithm/flow-network] For any such physical network, the flow coming into any intermediate node needs to equal the flow going out of that node.
[src:dinic-algorithm/flow-network] This conservation constraint is equivalent to Kirchhoff's current law.
[src:dinic-algorithm/flow-network] Flow networks also find applications in ecology: flow networks arise naturally when considering the flow of nutrients and energy between different organisms in a food web.
[src:dinic-algorithm/flow-network] The mathematical problems associated with such networks are quite different from those that arise in networks of fluid or traffic flow.
[src:dinic-algorithm/flow-network] The field of ecosystem network analysis, developed by Robert Ulanowicz and others, involves using concepts from information theory and thermodynamics to study the evolution of these networks over time.
[src:dinic-algorithm/flow-network] The simplest and most common problem using flow networks is to find what is called the maximum flow, which provides the largest possible total flow from the source to the sink in a given graph.
[src:dinic-algorithm/flow-network] There are many other problems which can be solved using max flow algorithms, if they are appropriately modeled as flow networks, such as bipartite matching, the assignment problem and the transportation problem.
[src:dinic-algorithm/flow-network] Maximum flow problems can be solved in polynomial time with various algorithms (see table).
[src:dinic-algorithm/flow-network] The max-flow min-cut theorem states that finding a maximal network flow is equivalent to finding a cut of minimum capacity that separates the source and the sink, where a cut is the division of vertices such that the source is in one division and the sink is in another.
[src:dinic-algorithm/flow-network] In a multi-commodity flow problem, you have multiple sources and sinks, and various "commodities" which are to flow from a given source to a given sink.
[src:dinic-algorithm/flow-network] This could be for example various goods that are produced at various factories, and are to be delivered to various given customers through the *same* transportation network.
[src:dinic-algorithm/flow-network] In a minimum cost flow problem, each edge $u,v$ has a given cost $k(u,v)$ , and the cost of sending the flow $f(u,v)$ across the edge is $f(u,v)\cdot k(u,v)$ .
[src:dinic-algorithm/flow-network] The objective is to send a given amount of flow from the source to the sink, at the lowest possible price.
[src:dinic-algorithm/flow-network] In a circulation problem, you have a lower bound $\ell (u,v)$ on the edges, in addition to the upper bound $c(u,v)$ .
[src:dinic-algorithm/flow-network] Often, flow conservation holds for *all* nodes in a circulation problem, and there is a connection from the sink back to the source.
[src:dinic-algorithm/flow-network] In this way, you can dictate the total flow with $\ell (t,s)$ and $c(t,s)$ .
[src:dinic-algorithm/flow-network] The flow *circulates* through the network, hence the name of the problem.
[src:dinic-algorithm/flow-network] In a **network with gains** or **generalized network** each edge has a **gain**, a real number (not zero) such that, if the edge has gain *g*, and an amount *x* flows into the edge at its tail, then an amount *gx* flows out at the head.
[src:dinic-algorithm/flow-network] In a **source localization problem**, an algorithm tries to identify the most likely source node of information diffusion through a partially observed network.
[src:dinic-algorithm/flow-network] This can be done in linear time for trees and cubic time for arbitrary networks and has applications ranging from tracking mobile phone users to identifying the originating source of disease outbreaks.
[src:dinic-algorithm/max-flow-min-cut-theorem] For example, imagine a network of pipes carrying water from a reservoir (the source) to a city (the sink).
[src:dinic-algorithm/max-flow-min-cut-theorem] Each pipe has a capacity representing the maximum amount of water that can flow through it per unit of time.
[src:dinic-algorithm/max-flow-min-cut-theorem] The max-flow min-cut theorem tells us that the maximum amount of water that can reach the city is limited by the smallest total capacity of any set of pipes that, if cut, would completely isolate the reservoir from the city.
[src:dinic-algorithm/max-flow-min-cut-theorem] This smallest total capacity is the min-cut.
[src:dinic-algorithm/max-flow-min-cut-theorem] So, if there's a bottleneck in the pipe network, represented by a small min-cut, that bottleneck will determine the overall maximum flow of water to the city.
[src:dinic-algorithm/max-flow-min-cut-theorem] This is a special case of the duality theorem for linear programs and can be used to derive Menger's theorem and the Kőnig–Egerváry theorem.
[src:dinic-algorithm/max-flow-min-cut-theorem] The theorem equates two quantities: the maximum flow through a network, and the minimum capacity of a cut of the network.
[src:dinic-algorithm/max-flow-min-cut-theorem] To state the theorem, each of these notions must first be defined.
[src:dinic-algorithm/max-flow-min-cut-theorem] A flow can be visualized as a physical flow of a fluid through the network, following the direction of each edge.
[src:dinic-algorithm/max-flow-min-cut-theorem] where as above s is the source and t is the sink of the network.
[src:dinic-algorithm/max-flow-min-cut-theorem] In the fluid analogy, it represents the amount of fluid entering the network at the source.
[src:dinic-algorithm/max-flow-min-cut-theorem] Because of the conservation axiom for flows, this is the same as the amount of flow leaving the network at the sink.
[src:dinic-algorithm/max-flow-min-cut-theorem] The maximum flow problem asks for the largest flow on a given network.
[src:dinic-algorithm/max-flow-min-cut-theorem] The other half of the max-flow min-cut theorem refers to a different aspect of a network: the collection of cuts.
[src:dinic-algorithm/max-flow-min-cut-theorem] That is, an *s*-*t* cut is a division of the vertices of the network into two parts, with the source in one part and the sink in the other.
[src:dinic-algorithm/max-flow-min-cut-theorem] Thus, if all the edges in the cut-set of C are removed, then no positive flow is possible, because there is no path in the resulting graph from the source to the sink.
[src:dinic-algorithm/max-flow-min-cut-theorem] There are typically many cuts in a graph, but cuts with smaller weights are often more difficult to find.
[src:dinic-algorithm/max-flow-min-cut-theorem] such that the capacity of the s-t cut is minimal.
[src:dinic-algorithm/max-flow-min-cut-theorem] In the above situation, one can prove that the value of any flow through a network is less than or equal to the capacity of any *s-t* cut, and that furthermore a flow with maximal value and a cut with minimal capacity exist.
[src:dinic-algorithm/max-flow-min-cut-theorem] The main theorem links the maximum flow value with the minimum cut capacity of the network.
[src:dinic-algorithm/max-flow-min-cut-theorem] The maximum value of an s-t flow is equal to the minimum capacity over all s-t cuts.
[src:dinic-algorithm/max-flow-min-cut-theorem] The figure on the right shows a flow in a network.
[src:dinic-algorithm/max-flow-min-cut-theorem] The numerical annotation on each arrow, in the form *f*/*c*, indicates the flow (*f*) and the capacity (*c*) of the arrow.
[src:dinic-algorithm/max-flow-min-cut-theorem] The flows emanating from the source total five (2+3=5), as do the flows into the sink (2+3=5), establishing that the flow's value is 5.
[src:dinic-algorithm/max-flow-min-cut-theorem] The capacities of the edges that cross this cut are 3 and 2, giving a cut capacity of 3+2=5.
[src:dinic-algorithm/max-flow-min-cut-theorem] The value of the flow is equal to the capacity of the cut, showing that the flow is a maximal flow and the cut is a minimal cut.
[src:dinic-algorithm/max-flow-min-cut-theorem] Note that the flow through each of the two arrows that connect *S* to *T* is at full capacity; this is always the case: a minimal cut represents a 'bottleneck' of the system.
[src:dinic-algorithm/max-flow-min-cut-theorem] The max-flow problem and min-cut problem can be formulated as two primal-dual linear programs.
[src:dinic-algorithm/max-flow-min-cut-theorem] The dual LP is obtained using the algorithm described in dual linear program: the variables and sign constraints of the dual correspond to the constraints of the primal, and the constraints of the dual correspond to the variables and sign constraints of the primal.
[src:dinic-algorithm/max-flow-min-cut-theorem] The resulting LP requires some explanation.
[src:dinic-algorithm/max-flow-min-cut-theorem] The minimization objective sums the capacity over all the edges that are contained in the cut.
[src:dinic-algorithm/max-flow-min-cut-theorem] Note that, since this is a minimization problem, we do not have to guarantee that an edge is *not* in the cut - we only have to guarantee that each edge that should be in the cut, is summed in the objective function.
[src:dinic-algorithm/max-flow-min-cut-theorem] The maximum flow problem can be formulated as the maximization of the electrical current through a network composed of nonlinear resistive elements.
[src:dinic-algorithm/max-flow-min-cut-theorem] In this formulation, the limit of the current *I*in between the input terminals of the electrical network as the input voltage *V*in approaches $\infty$ , is equal to the weight of the minimum-weight cut set.
[src:dinic-algorithm/max-flow-min-cut-theorem] In other words, the amount of *flow* passing through a vertex cannot exceed its capacity.
[src:dinic-algorithm/max-flow-min-cut-theorem] Define an *s-t cut* to be the set of vertices and edges such that for any path from *s* to *t*, the path contains a member of the cut.
[src:dinic-algorithm/max-flow-min-cut-theorem] In this case, the *capacity of the cut* is the sum of the capacity of each edge and vertex in it.
[src:dinic-algorithm/max-flow-min-cut-theorem] In this new definition, the **generalized max-flow min-cut theorem** states that the maximum value of an s-t flow is equal to the minimum capacity of an s-t cut in the new sense.
[src:dinic-algorithm/max-flow-min-cut-theorem] In the undirected edge-disjoint paths problem, we are given an undirected graph *G* = (*V*, *E*) and two vertices s and t, and we have to find the maximum number of edge-disjoint s-t paths in G.
[src:dinic-algorithm/max-flow-min-cut-theorem] In the project selection problem, there are n projects and m machines.
[src:dinic-algorithm/max-flow-min-cut-theorem] Each project pi yields revenue *r*(*pi*) and each machine qj costs *c*(*qj*) to purchase.
[src:dinic-algorithm/max-flow-min-cut-theorem] We want to select a subset of the project, and purchase a subset of the machines, to maximize the total profit (revenue of the selected projects minus cost of the purchased machines).
[src:dinic-algorithm/max-flow-min-cut-theorem] We must obey the following constraint: each project specifies a set of machines which must be purchased if the project is selected.
[src:dinic-algorithm/max-flow-min-cut-theorem] The above minimization problem can then be formulated as a minimum-cut problem by constructing a network, where the source is connected to the projects with capacity *r*(*pi*), and the sink is connected by the machines with capacity *c*(*qj*).
[src:dinic-algorithm/max-flow-min-cut-theorem] An edge (*pi*, *qj*) with *infinite* capacity is added if project pi requires machine qj.
[src:dinic-algorithm/max-flow-min-cut-theorem] The s-t cut-set represents the projects and machines in P and Q respectively.
[src:dinic-algorithm/max-flow-min-cut-theorem] By the max-flow min-cut theorem, one can solve the problem as a maximum flow problem.
[src:dinic-algorithm/max-flow-min-cut-theorem] The minimum capacity of an s-t cut is 250 and the sum of the revenue of each project is 450; therefore the maximum profit *g* is 450 − 250 = 200, by selecting projects *p*2 and *p*3.
[src:dinic-algorithm/max-flow-min-cut-theorem] The idea here is to 'flow' each project's profits through the 'pipes' of its machines.
[src:dinic-algorithm/max-flow-min-cut-theorem] If we cannot fill the pipe from a machine, the machine's return is less than its cost, and the min cut algorithm will find it cheaper to cut the project's profit edge instead of the machine's cost edge.
[src:dinic-algorithm/max-flow-min-cut-theorem] In the image segmentation problem, there are n pixels.
[src:dinic-algorithm/max-flow-min-cut-theorem] Each pixel i can be assigned a foreground value fi or a background value bi.
[src:dinic-algorithm/max-flow-min-cut-theorem] There is a penalty of pij if pixels i, j are adjacent and have different assignments.
[src:dinic-algorithm/max-flow-min-cut-theorem] The problem is to assign pixels to foreground or background such that the sum of their values minus the penalties is maximum.
[src:dinic-algorithm/max-flow-min-cut-theorem] The above minimization problem can be formulated as a minimum-cut problem by constructing a network where the source (orange node) is connected to all the pixels with capacity fi, and the sink (purple node) is connected by all the pixels with capacity bi.
[src:dinic-algorithm/max-flow-min-cut-theorem] Two edges (i, j) and (j, i) with pij capacity are added between two adjacent pixels.
[src:dinic-algorithm/max-flow-min-cut-theorem] The s-t cut-set then represents the pixels assigned to the foreground in P and pixels assigned to background in Q.
[src:dinic-algorithm/max-flow-min-cut-theorem] "Determining a maximal steady state flow from one point to another in a network subject to capacity limitations on arcs ... was posed to the authors in the spring of 1955 by T.E.
[src:dinic-algorithm/max-flow-min-cut-theorem] Harris, who, in conjunction with General F.
[src:dinic-algorithm/max-flow-min-cut-theorem] Ross (Ret.) had formulated a simplified model of railway traffic flow, and pinpointed this particular problem as the central one suggested by the model.
[src:dinic-algorithm/max-flow-min-cut-theorem] It was not long after this until the main result, Theorem 5.1, which we call the max-flow min-cut theorem, was conjectured and established.
[src:dinic-algorithm/max-flow-min-cut-theorem] Let *G* = (*V*, *E*) be a network (directed graph) with s and t being the source and the sink of G respectively.
[src:dinic-algorithm/max-flow-min-cut-theorem] Consider the flow *f* computed for G by Ford–Fulkerson algorithm.
[src:dinic-algorithm/max-flow-min-cut-theorem] Now, we know, $value(f)=f_{out}(A)-f_{in}(A)$ for any subset of vertices, A.
[src:dinic-algorithm/max-flow-min-cut-theorem] Both of the above statements prove that the capacity of cut obtained in the above described manner is equal to the flow obtained in the network.
[src:dinic-algorithm/max-flow-min-cut-theorem] Also, the flow was obtained by Ford-Fulkerson algorithm, so it is the max-flow of the network as well.
[src:dinic-algorithm/max-flow-min-cut-theorem] Also, since any flow in the network is always less than or equal to capacity of every cut possible in a network, the above described cut is also the min-cut which obtains the max-flow.
[src:dinic-algorithm/max-flow-min-cut-theorem] A corollary from this proof is that the maximum flow through any set of edges in a cut of a graph is equal to the minimum capacity of all previous cuts.
[src:dinic-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] In optimization theory, **maximum flow problems** involve finding a feasible flow through a flow network that obtains the maximum possible flow rate.
[src:dinic-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] The maximum flow problem can be seen as a special case of more complex network flow problems, such as the circulation problem.
[src:dinic-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] The maximum value of an s-t flow (i.e., flow from source s to sink t) is equal to the minimum capacity of an s-t cut (i.e., cut severing s from t) in the network, as stated in the max-flow min-cut theorem.
[src:dinic-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] The maximum flow problem was first formulated in 1954 by T.
[src:dinic-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] Ross as a simplified model of Soviet railway traffic flow.
[src:dinic-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] Fulkerson created the first known algorithm, the Ford–Fulkerson algorithm.
[src:dinic-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] In their 1955 paper, Ford and Fulkerson wrote that the problem of Harris and Ross is formulated as follows (see p.
[src:dinic-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] where [11] refers to the 1955 secret report *Fundamentals of a Method for Evaluating Rail net Capacities* by Harris and Ross (see p.
[src:dinic-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] The algorithms of Sherman and Kelner, Lee, Orecchia and Sidford, respectively, find an approximately optimal maximum flow but only work in undirected graphs.
[src:dinic-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] Orlin published a paper describing an $O(|V||E|)$ algorithm.
[src:dinic-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] Liu, Richard Peng, Maximilian Probst Gutenberg, and Sushant Sachdeva published an almost-linear time algorithm running in $O(|E|^{1+o(1)})$ for the minimum-cost flow problem of which the maximum flow problem is a particular case.
[src:dinic-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] For the single-source shortest path (SSSP) problem with negative weights – another particular case of a minimum-cost flow problem – an algorithm running in almost-linear time has also been reported.
[src:dinic-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] Both algorithms were deemed best papers at the 2022 Symposium on Foundations of Computer Science.
[src:dinic-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] Note that several maximum flows may exist, and if arbitrary real (or even arbitrary rational) values of flow are permitted (instead of just integers), there is either exactly one maximum flow, or infinitely many, since there are infinitely many linear combinations of the base maximum flows.
[src:dinic-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] In other words, if we send x units of flow on edge u in one maximum flow, and $y>x$ units of flow on u in another maximum flow, then for each $\Delta \in [0,y-x]$ we can send $x+\Delta$ units on u and route the flow on remaining edges accordingly, to obtain another maximum flow.
[src:dinic-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] If flow values can be any real or rational numbers, then there are infinitely many such $\Delta$ values for each pair $x,y$ .
[src:dinic-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] The following tables show the historical development of algorithms for solving the maximum flow problem.
[src:dinic-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] Many of the listed publications include similar tables comparing their results to earlier works.
[src:dinic-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] A strongly-polynomial time algorithm has polynomial time bounds that depend only on the number of inputs, but do not depend on the magnitude of these numbers.
[src:dinic-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] Here, the inputs are the vertices (numbered below as V ) and edges (numbered as E ).
[src:dinic-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] The complexity of each algorithm is stated using big O notation.
[src:dinic-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] In parallel to the development of strongly-polynomial flow algorithms, there has been a long line of pseudo-polynomial and weakly polynomial time bounds, whose running time depends on the magnitude of the input capacities.
[src:dinic-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] Here, the value U refers to the largest edge capacity after rescaling all capacities to integer values.
[src:dinic-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] If each edge in a flow network has integral capacity, then there exists an integral maximal flow.
[src:dinic-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] The claim is not only that the value of the flow is an integer, which follows directly from the max-flow min-cut theorem, but that the flow on *every edge* is integral.
[src:dinic-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] This is crucial for many combinatorial applications (see below), where the flow across an edge may encode whether the item corresponding to that edge is to be included in the set sought or not.
[src:dinic-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] Given a network $N=(V,E)$ with a set of sources $S=\{s_{1},\ldots ,s_{n}\}$ and a set of sinks $T=\{t_{1},\ldots ,t_{m}\}$ instead of only one source and one sink, we are to find the maximum flow across N .
[src:dinic-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] We can transform the multi-source multi-sink problem into a maximum flow problem by adding a *consolidated source* connecting to each vertex in S and a *consolidated sink*connected by each vertex in T (also known as *supersource* and *supersink*) with infinite capacity on each edge (See Fig.
[src:dinic-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] Given a bipartite graph $G=(X\cup Y,E)$ , we are to find a maximum cardinality matching in G , that is a matching that contains the largest possible number of edges.
[src:dinic-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] Then the value of the maximum flow in N is equal to the size of the maximum matching in G , and a maximum cardinality matching can be found by taking those edges that have flow 1 in an integral max-flow.
[src:dinic-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] Given a directed acyclic graph $G=(V,E)$ , we are to find the minimum number of vertex-disjoint paths to cover each vertex in V .
[src:dinic-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] Then it can be shown that $G'$ has a matching M of size m if and only if G has a vertex-disjoint path cover C containing m edges and $n-m$ paths, where n is the number of vertices in G .
[src:dinic-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] Therefore, the problem can be solved by finding the maximum cardinality matching in $G'$ instead.
[src:dinic-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] Assume we have found a matching M of $G'$ , and constructed the cover C from it.
[src:dinic-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] Intuitively, if two vertices $u_{\mathrm {out} },v_{\mathrm {in} }$ are matched in M , then the edge $(u,v)$ is contained in C .
[src:dinic-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] Similarly for each vertex $v_{\textrm {in}}$ in $G'$ – if it is matched, there is a single incoming edge into v in C ; otherwise v has no incoming edges in C .
[src:dinic-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] Thus no vertex has two incoming or two outgoing edges in C , which means all paths in C are vertex-disjoint.
[src:dinic-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] To show that the cover C has size $n-m$ , we start with an empty cover and build it incrementally.
[src:dinic-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] To add a vertex u to the cover, we can either add it to an existing path, or create a new path of length zero starting at that vertex.
[src:dinic-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] The former case is applicable whenever either $(u,v)\in E$ and some path in the cover starts at v , or $(v,u)\in E$ and some path ends at v .
[src:dinic-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] In the former case, the total number of edges in the cover is increased by 1 and the number of paths stays the same; in the latter case the number of paths is increased and the number of edges stays the same.
[src:dinic-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] It is now clear that after covering all n vertices, the sum of the number of paths and edges in the cover is n .
[src:dinic-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] Therefore, if the number of edges in the cover is m , the number of paths is $n-m$ .
[src:dinic-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] In other words, the amount of flow passing through a vertex cannot exceed its capacity.
[src:dinic-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] To find the maximum flow across N , we can transform the problem into the maximum flow problem in the original sense by expanding N .
[src:dinic-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] First, each $v\in V$ is replaced by $v_{\text{in}}$ and $v_{\text{out}}$ , where $v_{\text{in}}$ is connected by edges going into v and $v_{\text{out}}$ is connected to edges coming out from v , then assign capacity $c(v)$ to the edge connecting $v_{\text{in}}$ and $v_{\text{out}}$ (see Fig.
[src:dinic-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] In this expanded network, the vertex capacity constraint is removed and therefore the problem can be treated as the original maximum flow problem.
[src:dinic-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] Given a directed graph $G=(V,E)$ and two vertices s and t , we are to find the maximum number of paths from s to t .
[src:dinic-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] The paths must be independent, i.e., vertex-disjoint (except for s and t ).
[src:dinic-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] We can construct a network $N=(V,E)$ from G with vertex capacities, where the capacities of all vertices and all edges are 1 .
[src:dinic-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] Then the value of the maximum flow is equal to the maximum number of independent paths from s to t .
[src:dinic-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] In addition to the paths being edge-disjoint and/or vertex disjoint, the paths also have a length constraint: we count only paths whose length is exactly k , or at most k .
[src:dinic-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] Most variants of this problem are NP-complete, except for small values of k .
[src:dinic-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] A **closure** of a directed graph is a set of vertices *C*, such that no edges leave *C*.
[src:dinic-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] The **closure problem** is the task of finding the maximum-weight or minimum-weight closure in a vertex-weighted directed graph.
[src:dinic-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] It may be solved in polynomial time using a reduction to the maximum flow problem.
[src:dinic-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] In the baseball elimination problem there are *n* teams competing in a league.
[src:dinic-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] At a specific stage of the league season, *w**i* is the number of wins and *r**i* is the number of games left to play for team *i* and *r*ij is the number of games left against team *j*.
[src:dinic-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] A team is eliminated if it has no chance to finish the season in the first place.
[src:dinic-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] The task of the baseball elimination problem is to determine which teams are eliminated at each point during the season.
[src:dinic-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] Schwartz proposed a method which reduces this problem to maximum network flow.
[src:dinic-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] In this method a network is created to determine whether team *k* is eliminated.
[src:dinic-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] Let *G* = (*V*, *E*) be a network with *s*,*t* ∈ *V* being the source and the sink respectively.
[src:dinic-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] One adds a game node*ij* – which represents the number of plays between these two teams.
[src:dinic-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] We also add a team node for each team and connect each game node {*i*, *j*} with *i* < *j* to *V*, and connects each of them from *s* by an edge with capacity *r**ij* – which represents the number of plays between these two teams.
[src:dinic-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] We also add a team node for each team and connect each game node {*i*, *j*} with two team nodes *i* and *j* to ensure one of them wins.
[src:dinic-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] One does not need to restrict the flow value on these edges.
[src:dinic-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] Finally, edges are made from team node *i* to the sink node *t* and the capacity of *w**k* + *r**k* – *w**i* is set to prevent team *i* from winning more than *w**k* + *r**k*.
[src:dinic-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] In this method it is claimed team *k* is not eliminated if and only if a flow value of size *r*(*S* − {*k*}) exists in network *G*.
[src:dinic-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] In the mentioned article it is proved that this flow value is the maximum flow value from *s* to *t*.
[src:dinic-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] In the airline industry a major problem is the scheduling of the flight crews.
[src:dinic-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] The airline scheduling problem can be considered as an application of extended maximum network flow.
[src:dinic-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] The input of this problem is a set of flights *F* which contains the information about where and when each flight departs and arrives.
[src:dinic-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] In one version of airline scheduling the goal is to produce a feasible schedule with at most *k* crews.
[src:dinic-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] To solve this problem one uses a variation of the circulation problem called bounded circulation which is the generalization of network flow problems, with the added constraint of a lower bound on edge flows.
[src:dinic-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] Let *G* = (*V*, *E*) be a network with *s*,*t* ∈ *V* as the source and the sink nodes.
[src:dinic-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] For the source and destination of every flight *i*, one adds two nodes to *V*, node *s**i* as the source and node *d**i* as the destination node of flight *i*.
[src:dinic-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] An edge with capacity [0, 1] between each *d**i* and *t*.
[src:dinic-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] An edge with capacity [1, 1] between each pair of *s**i* and *d**i*.
[src:dinic-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] An edge with capacity [0, 1] between each *d**i* and *s**j*, if source *s**j* is reachable with a reasonable amount of time and cost from the destination of flight *i*.
[src:dinic-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] An edge with capacity [0, ∞] between *s* and *t*.
[src:dinic-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] In the mentioned method, it is claimed and proved that finding a flow value of *k* in *G* between *s* and *t* is equal to finding a feasible schedule for flight set *F* with at most *k* crews.
[src:dinic-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] Another version of airline scheduling is finding the minimum needed crews to perform all the flights.
[src:dinic-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] To find an answer to this problem, a bipartite graph *G'* = (*A* ∪ *B*, *E*) is created where each flight has a copy in set *A* and set *B*.
[src:dinic-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] If the same plane can perform flight *j* after flight *i*, *i*∈*A* is connected to *j*∈*B*.
[src:dinic-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] A matching in G' induces a schedule for *F* and obviously maximum bipartite matching in this graph produces an airline schedule with minimum number of crews.
[src:dinic-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] As it is mentioned in the Application part of this article, the maximum cardinality bipartite matching is an application of maximum flow problem.
[src:dinic-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] There are some factories that produce goods and some villages where the goods have to be delivered.
[src:dinic-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] They are connected by a networks of roads with each road having a capacity c for maximum goods that can flow through it.
[src:dinic-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] The problem is to find if there is a circulation that satisfies the demand.
[src:dinic-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] This problem can be transformed into a maximum-flow problem.
[src:dinic-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] Add a sink node t and add edges from all villages vi to t with capacity di where di is the demand rate of village vi.
[src:dinic-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] Let *G* = (*V*, *E*) be this new network.
[src:dinic-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] If there exists a circulation, looking at the max-flow solution would give the answer as to how much goods have to be sent on a particular road for satisfying the demands.
[src:dinic-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] The problem can be extended by adding a lower bound on the flow on some edges.
[src:dinic-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] In their book, Kleinberg and Tardos present an algorithm for segmenting an image.
[src:dinic-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] They present an algorithm to find the background and the foreground in an image.
[src:dinic-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] Indeed, for pixels in *A* (considered as the foreground), we gain *ai*; for all pixels in *B* (considered as the background), we gain *bi*.
[src:dinic-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] On the border, between two adjacent pixels *i* and *j*, we loose *pij*.
[src:dinic-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] We now construct the network whose nodes are the pixel, plus a source and a sink, see Figure on the right.
[src:dinic-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] We connect the source to pixel *i* by an edge of weight *ai*.
[src:dinic-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] We connect the pixel *i* to the sink by an edge of weight *bi*.
[src:dinic-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] We connect pixel *i* to pixel *j* with weight *pij*.
[src:dinic-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] Now, it remains to compute a minimum cut in that network (or equivalently a maximum flow).
[src:dinic-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] With negative constraints, the problem becomes strongly NP-hard even for simple networks.
[src:dinic-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] With positive constraints, the problem is polynomial if fractional flows are allowed, but may be strongly NP-hard when the flows must be integral.
[src:dinic-algorithm/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] In mathematical optimization, the **push–relabel algorithm** (alternatively, **preflow–push algorithm**) is an algorithm for computing maximum flows in a flow network.
[src:dinic-algorithm/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] The name "push–relabel" comes from the two basic operations used in the algorithm.
[src:dinic-algorithm/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] Throughout its execution, the algorithm maintains a "preflow" and gradually converts it into a maximum flow by moving flow locally between neighboring nodes using *push* operations under the guidance of an admissible network maintained by *relabel* operations.
[src:dinic-algorithm/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] In comparison, the Ford–Fulkerson algorithm performs global augmentations that send flow following paths from the source all the way to the sink.
[src:dinic-algorithm/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] The push–relabel algorithm is considered one of the most efficient maximum flow algorithms.
[src:dinic-algorithm/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] The generic algorithm has a strongly polynomial *O*(*V* 2*E*) time complexity, which is asymptotically more efficient than the *O*(*VE* 2) Edmonds–Karp algorithm.
[src:dinic-algorithm/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] Specific variants of the algorithms achieve even lower time complexities.
[src:dinic-algorithm/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] The variant based on the highest label node selection rule has *O*(*V* 2√*E*) time complexity and is generally regarded as the benchmark for maximum flow algorithms.
[src:dinic-algorithm/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] Subcubic *O*(*VE*log(*V* 2/*E*)) time complexity can be achieved using dynamic trees, although in practice it is less efficient.
[src:dinic-algorithm/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] The push–relabel algorithm has been extended to compute minimum cost flows.
[src:dinic-algorithm/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] The idea of distance labels has led to a more efficient augmenting path algorithm, which in turn can be incorporated back into the push–relabel algorithm to create a variant with even higher empirical performance.
[src:dinic-algorithm/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] A preflow is a flow in which the total amount flowing into a vertex may be greater than the total amount flowing out of it, allowing an algorithm to change the flow on a single arc.
[src:dinic-algorithm/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] This idea was originally conceived by Alexander V.
[src:dinic-algorithm/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] Karzanov and was published in 1974 in Soviet Mathematical Dokladi 15.
[src:dinic-algorithm/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] This pre-flow algorithm also used a push operation; however, it used distances in the auxiliary network to determine where to push the flow instead of a labeling system.
[src:dinic-algorithm/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] The push-relabel algorithm was designed by Andrew V.
[src:dinic-algorithm/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] The algorithm was initially presented in November 1986 in STOC '86: Proceedings of the eighteenth annual ACM symposium on Theory of computing, and then officially in October 1988 as an article in the *Journal of the ACM*.
[src:dinic-algorithm/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] Both papers detail a generic form of the algorithm terminating in *O*(*V* 2*E*) along with a *O*(*V* 3) sequential implementation, a *O*(*VE* log(*V* 2/*E*)) implementation using dynamic trees, and parallel/distributed implementation.
[src:dinic-algorithm/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] As explained in, Goldberg–Tarjan introduced distance labels by incorporating them into the parallel maximum flow algorithm of Yossi Shiloach and Uzi Vishkin.
[src:dinic-algorithm/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] The push–relabel algorithm uses a nonnegative integer valid **labeling function** which makes use of *distance labels*, or *heights*, on nodes to determine which arcs should be selected for the push operation.
[src:dinic-algorithm/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] This labeling function is denoted by 𝓁 : *V* → ℕ.
[src:dinic-algorithm/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] In the algorithm, the label values of s and t are fixed. 𝓁(*u*) is a lower bound of the unweighted distance from u to t in *G**f* if t is reachable from u.
[src:dinic-algorithm/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] If u has been disconnected from t, then 𝓁(*u*) − | *V* | is a lower bound of the unweighted distance from u to s.
[src:dinic-algorithm/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] As a result, if a valid labeling function exists, there are no *s*-*t* paths in *G**f* because no such paths can be longer than | *V* | − 1.
[src:dinic-algorithm/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] The **admissible network** *G̃**f* (*V*, *Ẽ**f* ) is composed of the set of arcs *e* ∈ *E**f* that are admissible.
[src:dinic-algorithm/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] For a fixed flow *f*, a vertex *v ∉*{*s, t*} is called **active** if it has positive excess with respect to *f*, i.e., *x**f* (*u*) > 0.
[src:dinic-algorithm/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] The algorithm starts by creating a residual graph, initializing the preflow values to zero and performing a set of saturating push operations on residual arcs (*s*, *v*) exiting the source, where *v* ∈ *V* \ {*s*}.
[src:dinic-algorithm/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] Similarly, the labels are initialized such that the label at the source is the number of nodes in the graph, 𝓁(*s*) = | *V* |, and all other nodes are given a label of zero.
[src:dinic-algorithm/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] Once the initialization is complete the algorithm repeatedly performs either the push or relabel operations against active nodes until no applicable operation can be performed.
[src:dinic-algorithm/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] The push operation applies on an admissible out-arc (*u*, *v*) of an active node u in *G**f*.
[src:dinic-algorithm/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] A push operation that causes *f* (*u*, *v*) to reach *c*(*u*, *v*) is called a **saturating push** since it uses up all the available capacity of the residual arc.
[src:dinic-algorithm/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] Otherwise, all of the excess at the node is pushed across the residual arc.
[src:dinic-algorithm/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] This is called an **unsaturating** or **non-saturating push**.
[src:dinic-algorithm/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] The relabel operation applies on an active node u which is neither the source nor the sink without any admissible out-arcs in *Gf*.
[src:dinic-algorithm/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] It modifies 𝓁(*u*) to be the minimum value such that an admissible out-arc is created.
[src:dinic-algorithm/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] Note that this always increases 𝓁(*u*) and never creates a steep arc, which is an arc (*u*, *v*) such that *c**f* (*u*, *v*) > 0, and 𝓁(*u*) > 𝓁(*v*) + 1.
[src:dinic-algorithm/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] After a push or relabel operation, 𝓁 remains a valid labeling function with respect to f.
[src:dinic-algorithm/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] For a push operation on an admissible arc (*u*, *v*), it may add an arc (*v*, *u*) to *Ef*, where 𝓁(*v*) = 𝓁(*u*) − 1 ≤ 𝓁(*u*) + 1; it may also remove the arc (*u*, *v*) from *E**f*, where it effectively removes the constraint 𝓁(*u*) ≤ 𝓁(*v*) + 1.
[src:dinic-algorithm/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] To see that a relabel operation on node u preserves the validity of 𝓁(*u*), notice that this is trivially guaranteed by definition for the out-arcs of *u* in *G**f*.
[src:dinic-algorithm/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] For the in-arcs of u in *G**f*, the increased 𝓁(*u*) can only satisfy the constraints less tightly, not violate them.
[src:dinic-algorithm/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] The generic push–relabel algorithm is used as a proof of concept only and does not contain implementation details on how to select an active node for the push and relabel operations.
[src:dinic-algorithm/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] This generic version of the algorithm will terminate in *O*(*V*2*E*).
[src:dinic-algorithm/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] Since 𝓁(*s*) = | *V* |, 𝓁(*t*) = 0, and there are no paths longer than | *V* | − 1 in *G**f*, in order for 𝓁(*s*) to satisfy the valid labeling condition s must be disconnected from t.
[src:dinic-algorithm/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] At initialisation, the algorithm fulfills this requirement by creating a pre-flow f that saturates all out-arcs of s, after which 𝓁(*v*) = 0 is trivially valid for all *v* ∈ *V* \ {*s*, *t*}.
[src:dinic-algorithm/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] After initialisation, the algorithm repeatedly executes an applicable push or relabel operation until no such operations apply, at which point the pre-flow has been converted into a maximum flow.
[src:dinic-algorithm/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] The algorithm maintains the condition that 𝓁 is a valid labeling during its execution.
[src:dinic-algorithm/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] This can be proven true by examining the effects of the push and relabel operations on the label function 𝓁.
[src:dinic-algorithm/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] The relabel operation increases the label value by the associated minimum plus one which will always satisfy the 𝓁(*u*) ≤ 𝓁(*v*) + 1 constraint.
[src:dinic-algorithm/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] The push operation can send flow from u to v if 𝓁(*u*) = 𝓁(*v*) + 1.
[src:dinic-algorithm/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] The addition of (*v*, *u*) to *G**f* will not affect the valid labeling since 𝓁(*v*) = 𝓁(*u*) − 1.
[src:dinic-algorithm/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] The deletion of (*u*, *v*) from *G**f* removes the corresponding constraint since the valid labeling property 𝓁(*u*) ≤ 𝓁(*v*) + 1 only applies to residual arcs in *G**f* .
[src:dinic-algorithm/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] If a preflow f and a valid labeling 𝓁 for f exists then there is no augmenting path from s to t in the residual graph *G**f* .
[src:dinic-algorithm/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] This can be proven by contradiction based on inequalities which arise in the labeling function when supposing that an augmenting path does exist.
[src:dinic-algorithm/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] If the algorithm terminates, then all nodes in *V* \ {*s*, *t*} are not active.
[src:dinic-algorithm/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] This means all *v* ∈ *V* \ {*s*, *t*} have no excess flow, and with no excess the preflow f obeys the flow conservation constraint and can be considered a normal flow.
[src:dinic-algorithm/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] This flow is the maximum flow according to the max-flow min-cut theorem since there is no augmenting path from s to t.
[src:dinic-algorithm/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] Therefore, the algorithm will return the maximum flow upon termination.
[src:dinic-algorithm/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] In order to bound the time complexity of the algorithm, we must analyze the number of push and relabel operations which occur within the main loop.
[src:dinic-algorithm/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] The numbers of relabel, saturating push and nonsaturating push operations are analyzed separately.
[src:dinic-algorithm/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] In the algorithm, the relabel operation can be performed at most (2| *V* | − 1)(| *V* | − 2) < 2| *V* |2 times.
[src:dinic-algorithm/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] This is because the labeling 𝓁(*u*) value for any node *u* can never decrease, and the maximum label value is at most 2| *V* | − 1 for all nodes.
[src:dinic-algorithm/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] This means the relabel operation could potentially be performed 2| *V* | − 1 times for all nodes *V* \ {*s*, *t*} (i.e. | *V* | − 2).
[src:dinic-algorithm/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] This results in a bound of *O*(*V* 2) for the relabel operation.
[src:dinic-algorithm/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] Each saturating push on an admissible arc (*u*, *v*) removes the arc from *G**f* .
[src:dinic-algorithm/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] For the arc to be reinserted into *G**f* for another saturating push, v must first be relabeled, followed by a push on the arc (*v*, *u*), then u must be relabeled.
[src:dinic-algorithm/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] In the process, 𝓁(*u*) increases by at least two.
[src:dinic-algorithm/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] Therefore, there are *O*(*V*) saturating pushes on (*u*, *v*), and the total number of saturating pushes is at most 2| *V* || *E* |.
[src:dinic-algorithm/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] This results in a time bound of *O*(*VE*) for the saturating push operations.
[src:dinic-algorithm/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] Bounding the number of nonsaturating pushes can be achieved via a potential argument.
[src:dinic-algorithm/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] We use the potential function Φ = Σ[*u* ∈ *V* ∧ *x**f* (*u*) > 0] 𝓁(*u*) (i.e. Φ is the sum of the labels of all active nodes).
[src:dinic-algorithm/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] It is obvious that Φ is 0 initially and stays nonnegative throughout the execution of the algorithm.
[src:dinic-algorithm/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] Both relabels and saturating pushes can increase Φ.
[src:dinic-algorithm/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] However, the value of Φ must be equal to 0 at termination since there cannot be any remaining active nodes at the end of the algorithm's execution.
[src:dinic-algorithm/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] This means that over the execution of the algorithm, the nonsaturating pushes must make up the difference of the relabel and saturating push operations in order for Φ to terminate with a value of 0.
[src:dinic-algorithm/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] The relabel operation can increase Φ by at most (2| *V* | − 1)(| *V* | − 2).
[src:dinic-algorithm/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] A saturating push on (*u*, *v*) activates v if it was inactive before the push, increasing Φ by at most 2| *V* | − 1.
[src:dinic-algorithm/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] Hence, the total contribution of all saturating pushes operations to Φ is at most (2| *V* | − 1)(2| *V* || *E* |).
[src:dinic-algorithm/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] A nonsaturating push on (*u*, *v*) always deactivates u, but it can also activate v as in a saturating push.
[src:dinic-algorithm/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] As a result, it decreases Φ by at least 𝓁(*u*) − 𝓁(*v*) = 1.
[src:dinic-algorithm/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] Since relabels and saturating pushes increase Φ, the total number of nonsaturating pushes must make up the difference of (2| *V* | − 1)(| *V* | − 2) + (2| *V* | − 1)(2| *V* || *E* |) ≤ 4| *V* |2| *E* |.
[src:dinic-algorithm/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] This results in a time bound of *O*(*V* 2*E*) for the nonsaturating push operations.
[src:dinic-algorithm/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] In sum, the algorithm executes *O*(*V* 2) relabels, *O*(*VE*) saturating pushes and *O*(*V* 2*E*) nonsaturating pushes.
[src:dinic-algorithm/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] Data structures can be designed to pick and execute an applicable operation in *O*(1) time.
[src:dinic-algorithm/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] Therefore, the time complexity of the algorithm is *O*(*V* 2*E*).
[src:dinic-algorithm/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] The following is a sample execution of the generic push-relabel algorithm, as defined above, on the following simple network flow graph diagram.
[src:dinic-algorithm/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] In the example, the *h* and *e* values denote the label 𝓁 and excess *x**f* , respectively, of the node during the execution of the algorithm.
[src:dinic-algorithm/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] Each residual graph in the example only contains the residual arcs with a capacity larger than zero.
[src:dinic-algorithm/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] Each residual graph may contain multiple iterations of the *perform operation* loop.
[src:dinic-algorithm/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] The example (but with initial flow of 0) can be run here interactively.
[src:dinic-algorithm/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] While the generic push–relabel algorithm has *O*(*V* 2*E*) time complexity, efficient implementations achieve *O*(*V* 3) or lower time complexity by enforcing appropriate rules in selecting applicable push and relabel operations.
[src:dinic-algorithm/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] The empirical performance can be further improved by heuristics.
[src:dinic-algorithm/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] The "current-arc" data structure is a mechanism for visiting the in- and out-neighbors of a node in the flow network in a static circular order.
[src:dinic-algorithm/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] If a singly linked list of neighbors is created for a node, the data structure can be as simple as a pointer into the list that steps through the list and rewinds to the head when it runs off the end.
[src:dinic-algorithm/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] Based on the "current-arc" data structure, the discharge operation can be defined.
[src:dinic-algorithm/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] A discharge operation applies on an active node and repeatedly pushes flow from the node until it becomes inactive, relabeling it as necessary to create admissible arcs in the process.
[src:dinic-algorithm/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] Finding the next admissible edge to push on has $O(1)$ amortized complexity.
[src:dinic-algorithm/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] The current-arc pointer only moves to the next neighbor when the edge to the current neighbor is saturated or non-admissible, and neither of these two properties can change until the active node u is relabelled.
[src:dinic-algorithm/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] Therefore, when the pointer runs off, there are no admissible unsaturated edges and we have to relabel the active node u , so having moved the pointer $O(V)$ times is paid for by the $O(V)$ relabel operation.
[src:dinic-algorithm/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] Definition of the discharge operation reduces the push–relabel algorithm to repeatedly selecting an active node to discharge.
[src:dinic-algorithm/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] Depending on the selection rule, the algorithm exhibits different time complexities.
[src:dinic-algorithm/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] For the sake of brevity, we ignore s and t when referring to the nodes in the following discussion.
[src:dinic-algorithm/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] The FIFO push–relabel algorithm organizes the active nodes into a queue.
[src:dinic-algorithm/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] The initial active nodes can be inserted in arbitrary order.
[src:dinic-algorithm/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] The algorithm always removes the node at the front of the queue for discharging.
[src:dinic-algorithm/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] Whenever an inactive node becomes active, it is appended to the back of the queue.
[src:dinic-algorithm/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] The algorithm has *O*(*V* 3) time complexity.
[src:dinic-algorithm/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] The relabel-to-front push–relabel algorithm organizes all nodes into a linked list and maintains the invariant that the list is topologically sorted with respect to the admissible network.
[src:dinic-algorithm/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] The algorithm scans the list from front to back and performs a discharge operation on the current node if it is active.
[src:dinic-algorithm/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] If the node is relabeled, it is moved to the front of the list, and the scan is restarted from the front.
[src:dinic-algorithm/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] The algorithm also has *O*(*V* 3) time complexity.
[src:dinic-algorithm/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] The highest-label push–relabel algorithm organizes all nodes into buckets indexed by their labels.
[src:dinic-algorithm/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] The algorithm always selects an active node with the largest label to discharge.
[src:dinic-algorithm/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] The algorithm has $O(V^{2}{\sqrt {E}})$ time complexity.
[src:dinic-algorithm/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] If the lowest-label selection rule is used instead, the time complexity becomes *O*(*V* 2*E*).
[src:dinic-algorithm/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] Although in the description of the generic push–relabel algorithm above, 𝓁(*u*) is set to zero for each node *u* other than s and t at the beginning, it is preferable to perform a backward breadth-first search from t to compute exact labels.
[src:dinic-algorithm/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] The algorithm is typically separated into two phases.
[src:dinic-algorithm/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] Phase one computes a maximum pre-flow by discharging only active nodes whose labels are below n.
[src:dinic-algorithm/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] Phase two converts the maximum preflow into a maximum flow by returning excess flow that cannot reach t to s.
[src:dinic-algorithm/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] It can be shown that phase two has *O*(*VE*) time complexity regardless of the order of push and relabel operations and is therefore dominated by phase one.
[src:dinic-algorithm/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] Alternatively, it can be implemented using flow decomposition.
[src:dinic-algorithm/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] Heuristics are crucial to improving the empirical performance of the algorithm.
[src:dinic-algorithm/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] Two commonly used heuristics are the gap heuristic and the global relabeling heuristic.
[src:dinic-algorithm/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] The gap heuristic detects gaps in the labeling function.
[src:dinic-algorithm/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] If there is a label 0 < 𝓁*'* < | *V* | for which there is no node u such that 𝓁(*u*) = 𝓁*'*, then any node u with 𝓁*'* < 𝓁(*u*) < | *V* | has been disconnected from t and can be relabeled to (| *V* | + 1) immediately.
[src:dinic-algorithm/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] The global relabeling heuristic periodically performs backward breadth-first search from t in *G**f* to compute the exact labels of the nodes.
[src:dinic-algorithm/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] Both heuristics skip unhelpful relabel operations, which are a bottleneck of the algorithm and contribute to the ineffectiveness of dynamic trees.
